cs.DC, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.NE, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with a communication channel and algorithms for assigning names to nodes, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of randomization and analysis of expected time and probability of error suggest that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of communication channels and information theory concepts such as beeps and instantaneous transmission suggest that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The use of randomness and optimization suggest that it could belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the use of anonymous nodes and the need for contiguous segments of positive integers suggest that it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
